.TH LMDBG-RUN 1 "May 9, 2009" "" ""
.SH NAME
lmdbg-run \- run program and traces the malloc/realloc/free calls
.SH SYNOPSIS
.BI lmdbg-run " [OPTIONS] <prog> [args...]"
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B lmdbg-run
lmdbg-run runs an external command
.I prog args
and creates a log file where all
invocations of
.IR malloc ", " calloc ", " realloc ", " memalign ", "
.IR posix_memalign " and " free
are registered with the following information: full stacktrace
(addresses), input argument(s) (requested size and/or address) and
result value (returned address, if any).  All stacktraces may
alternatively be sent to a pipe. Example for
.B lmdbg-run
output:
.VB

 realloc ( 0xbb901800 , 777 ) --> 0xbb901c00
  0xbbbe58e8
  0xbbbe5a37
  0x8048764
  0x8048584
  0x80484e7

.VE
This output means that
.I realloc
function was given pointer 0xbb901800 and 777
bytes was requested. As a result
.I realloc
returned address 0xbb901c00.
Addresses 0xbbbe58e8, 0xbbbe5a37 etc. are a part of stacktrace.  Another example:
.VB

$ cat tests/test2.c
#include <stdlib.h>

int main ()
{
   void *p1 = NULL;
   void *p2 = NULL;

   p1 = malloc (555);
   p2 = realloc (p2, 666);
   p2 = realloc (p2, 777);
   p2 = realloc (p2, 888);

   return 0;
}
$ cc -O0 -g -o _test2 tests/test2.c
$ lmdbg-run -o _log ./_test2 
$ cat _log
malloc ( 555 ) --> 0xbb901400
 0xbbbe58e8
 0xbbbe5b03
 0x8048738
 0x8048584
 0x80484e7
realloc ( NULL , 666 ) --> 0xbb901800
 0xbbbe58e8
 0xbbbe5a37
 0x804874e
 0x8048584
 0x80484e7
realloc ( 0xbb901800 , 777 ) --> 0xbb901c00
 0xbbbe58e8
 0xbbbe5a37
 0x8048764
 0x8048584
 0x80484e7
realloc ( 0xbb901c00 , 888 ) --> 0xbb901800
 0xbbbe58e8
 0xbbbe5a37
 0x804877a
 0x8048584
 0x80484e7
$

.VE
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.B "-h"
display help message.
.TP
.BI "-V"
Display the lmdbg version.
.TP
.BI "-o" " filename"
Specify the log file.
.TP
.BI "-p" " pipe"
Send all stacktraces to the pipe, not to the log file.
.TP
.B "-n"
Do not enable logging on startup, sending SIGUSR1 signal to the process
enables it.
.TP
.BI "-T" " skip"
A number of addresses to skip from the top of stacktrace (farther from function main).
.TP
.BI "-B" " skip"
A number of addresses to skip from the bottom of stacktrace (nearer to function main).
.TP
.BI "-M" " maximum"
Limit for a number of addresses in a stacktrace.
.TP
.B "-v"
Enable verbose mode.
.SH ENVIRONMENT
.TP
.B LMDBG_LIB
Path to LD_PRELOAD'ed liblmdbg dynamic library. It defaults to
@libdir@/liblmdbg.so
.SH EXAMPLES
.VB
lmdbg-run -h
lmdbg-run -V
lmdbg-run -o _log ./my_app &&
  lmdbg-leaks _log > _log_leaks &&
  lmdbg-sym ./my_app _log_leaks > _log_leaks2 &&
  lmdbg-sysleaks -s _log_leaks2 > _log_final
lmdbg-run -B2 -M6 -p 'lmdbg-leaks | lmdbg-sym -p > _log' ./my_app <args>
.VE
.SH NOTES
Full stacktrace allows you to analyse your application on per-module
basis, i.e.  you can determine what libraries and/or components require
more memory than others and why. See
.B lmdbg-stat
and
.BR lmdbg-sort .
.SH BUGS
At the moment
.B lmdbg-run
relies on several GCC's extension including __builtin_return_address,
__builtin_frame_address, __attribute__((constructor)) and
__attribute__((destructor)). Besides GCC these extensions are
supported by Intel C compiler. If you have a solution that works for
other compilers let me now ;-)
